<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
	<meta charset="UTF-8">
	<title>Random Thoughts</title>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
	<link href='http://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Indie+Flower' rel='stylesheet' type='text/css'>
</head>
<body>
	<div id="black"></div>

	<div id="wrapper">
		<div id="main">
			<h1 id="header">Random Thoughts</h1>
			<div id="thought" class="oval-thought-border">
			<h1 id="filler"></h1>
			</div>
			<button id="button2" class="button"> Get Thought</button>
			<input type="text" method="post" id="input">
			<button id="button" class="button">Add Thought</button>
		</div>

		<div id="info">
			<h2 class="titles">What is the Random Thought API?</h2>
			<div id="what" class='infos'>
				<p> The Random Thought API allows you to query it's user-created content using ajax requests. Anyone can add their random thoughts to the databse and the API dishes out a random one. It's funny, crazy, and sometimes downright dangerous. But it's all in good fun. Use is to brighten your day, or even as a fun way to test text in your website!
			</div>

			<h2 class="titles">How to use the Random thought API</h2>
			<div id="how" class='infos'>
				<p>Using the Random Thought API is easy! Simply send a get request to the following url and we'll send you back an JSON object with a random thought! Here is the standard API end point:</p>
				<div class="gray route">
					<p> http://randomthoughts.link/thoughts </p>
				</div>
				
			</div>

			<h2 class="titles">Specifying how many thoughts you want</h2>
			<div id="amount" class="infos">
				<p>You can specify how many thoughts you want to get by specifying the "amount" query parameter in the url. Here is an example:</p>
				<div class="gray route">
					<p> http://randomthoughts.link/thoughts?amount=2 </p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h2 class="titles">Searching for key words</h2>
			<div id="search" class="infos">
				<p>You can return thoughts with specified key words using the search route and specifying the keywords query parameter. Here is an example: </p>
				<div class="gray route">
					<p> http://randomthoughts.link/thoughts/search?keyword=blah </p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h2 class="titles">What is the exact JSON object that this API sends?</h2>
			<div id="object" class='infos'>
				<p>Here is the JSON object that the API sends:</p>
				<div id="json" class="gray route">
				<pre><code>
{	results: [
		{                         
			"thought": "Thought is here"
			"created_at": "time"
		}
	],
	status:{
		status: "Successfull"
	}
}
				</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>The results array will be populated with how many thougts are being given.</p>
			</div>

			<h2 class="titles">Getting word frequencies for thoughts</h2>
			<div id="search" class="infos">
				<p>You can return thoughts with specified key words using the search route and specifying the keywords query parameter. Here is an example: </p>
				<div class="gray route">
					<p> http://randomthoughts.link/thoughts/word_freq </p>
				</div>
				<p>By default, this request will get the top 50 words. You can request to get a smaller number of words by passing an "amount" query parameter with the request. However, 50 is the most you can get.</p>
			</div>

			<h2 class="titles">The JSON that will be returned from frequencies</h2>
			<div id="req" class='infos'>
				<p>Here is the JSON object that the API sends for a word frequency request:</p>
				<div id="json" class="gray route">
				<pre><code>
{	results: [
		{                         
			"word": "Word"
			"times": "number of times appears"
		}
	],
	status:{
		status: "Successfull"
	}
}
				</code></pre>
				</div>
				<p>The results array will be populated with how many words have been asked for.</p>
			</div>

		</div>

	</div>



	<script type="text/javascript" src="main.js"></script>
</body>
</html>